<br>
This was settled out of court, no details of the settlement are known -- that I'm aware of anyway, and I never paid much attention.<br>
<br>
The second was in 2000 by UO's volunteer guides (whatever they're called).  They believe that they were treated as employees and thus felt that they were deserved to be paid as employees, including backwages.  This is laughable for so many reasons.  I don't know how this was resolved, but I don't believe that it got very far.  I only really remember what I read on Lums.<br>
<br>
Verant may not be a smart company, but Sony is a very smart corporation and has likely been very aware of what's happened with other games and I'm sure that EQ's EULA reflects that.  Don't doubt that changing the system requirements for the game wasn't passed before a team of lawyers before they announced Luclin.<br>
<br>
I'm not anywhere close to a lawyer, but I do believe that Sony is covered.  I believe in the strength of EULA's.  I don't believe that a country that is *famous* worldwide for insane and successful law suits that they would not have been rendered useless otherwise.<br>
<br>
I'm against law suits of this nature.  Progress comes at a cost, and I think that problems that VI has experienced were almost unavoidable.  I think they've learned why so many FPS games have limited content test versions available to everyone to download months before the release so that they can nail down bugs that come with modern 3D engines.  At the same time, it's understandable why a company wouldn't want to do this.<br>
<br>
Despite the problems that they've had, I do applaud VI for pushing the envelope the way they did with this engine.  A lot of people love to compare FPS game engines to EQ, but those games are marginal in terms of the sheer number of textures and displayed polys.  I think that the expansion is technically and graphically impressive..  but that's totally subjective.<br>
<br>
I would prefer this over an outdated looking game that no longer attracts new gamers to its community and dies a slow death.<br>
<br>
